did.unittitle: Office of the Board of Trustees Records
did.abstract: This collection contains the records of the activities of the Board of Trustees beginning in 1848.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Records containing information related to student education, staff and faculty employment, and Board of Trustees records are closed for 75 years from the date of creation. This collection may require review before it is available for use. Please contact DCA for further details.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Transferred by the Board of Trustees, 2006 -- 2019.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is organized into 21 series: Full Board, Executive Committee, Academic Affairs Committee, Administration and Finance Committee, Audit Committee, Honorary Degree Committee working papers and subject files, Committee on Trusteeship, University Advancement Committee, Compensation Committee, Subcommittee Buildings and Grounds, Subject Files, Board of Visitors Committee, Investment Committee, Compiled Subject Files, Artifacts and photographs, Office files, Trustees Weekend Working Papers and Minutes, Financial and Investment Records, Campaign Committees, Student Affairs Committee, and Unprocessed accessions.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: In 1851, a Board of Trustees was nominated by the subscribers to replace the temporary Board created at the 1847 Educational Convention of the Universalist Church. The new Board selected a site and drew up the governing rules for the new College.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Office of the Board of Trustees Records, 1848 -- 2019. Tufts University. Digital Collections and Archives. Medford, MA.

processinfo.head: Processing status
processinfo.p: This collection is partially processed. Accessions from 2016-2018 were processed by Leah Edelman in 2017-2018. Accessions from 2019 were processed by Margaret Peachy in 2019. December 2019 accessions were processed by Jane Kelly in 2020. Materials were bagged using Bagger, zipped using 7-Zip, and ingested to the Dark Archive. Received chronological order was maintained. A file-level inventory was created, and series and collection-level description were updated at the time of processing.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains the records of the activities of the Board of Trustees from 1848 on. The bulk of these materials are arranged in chronological order by the date on which the meeting occurred. The collection contains meeting announcements, agendas, minutes, memos, reports, clippings, photographs, correspondence, event records, budget materials, policies, strategic plans, degree lists, honorary degree files, and commencement programs. Files labeled "working papers" contain meeting announcements, agendas, minutes, letters, memos, and supplemental material (i.e., reports and newspaper and journal articles) related to the specific meeting. Although the earliest material in the collections dates to the founding of the college, working papers of the full board meetings and various committee meetings were not regularly kept until the fall of 1974.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Some material in this collection may be protected by copyright and other rights. Please see "Reproductions and Use" on the Digital Collections and Archives website for more information about reproductions and permission to publish. Copyright to all materials created by Tufts University employees in the course of their work is held by the Trustees of Tufts University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains Tufts University's Full Board of Trustees documents from 1851 to the 2000. The bulk of these materials are arranged in chronological order by the date on which the meeting occurred. Folders contain meeting announcements, agendas, minutes, letters, memoranda, and supplemental material (i.e., reports and newspaper and journal articles).

The Board has the authority to carry out all lawful functions permitted by the bylaws and include but are not limited to the following: reviewing and approving the university's mission and purposes; appointing the President; establishing the conditions of employment of key officers; supporting the President and assessing his performance; reviewing and approving proposed major changes in the academic programs; approving institutional policies bearing on faculty appointments; approving the annual budget; monitoring the university's financial condition; fundraising; authorizing debt financing and loans; authorizing construction; approving degrees; and reviewing board performance.
Although the earliest material dates to the founding of the college, the working papers of the Full Board meetings were not regularly kept until the fall of 1974.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by meeting date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains material from Tufts University's Executive Committee from 1855 to 2000. Folders contain meeting announcements, agendas, minutes, letters, memoranda, and supplemental material (i.e., reports and current event materials). From 1855 to 1962, the work of the Executive Committee is captured in Secretary's meeting notes.
The Executive Committee makes decisions for the entire Board when the board is not in session. Its decisions carry the weight of the full Board.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by committee meeting date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains material from Tufts University's Academic Affairs Committee from the 1960s to 2000. Folders contain meeting announcements, agendas, minutes, letters, memoranda, and supplemental material (reports and memoranda regarding particular schools and faculty appointments). There is a small portion of this series from 1964 to 1984 subtitled the Education Policy Committee pertaining to academic affairs. The Academic Affairs Committee replaced the Educational Policy Committee in 1982.

Also includes operating reports and correspondence of the Institute for Foreign Policy Analysis, Inc. IFPA, founded in 1976, "is an independent, nonpartisan research organization that conducts research, publishes studies, convenes seminars and conferences, promotes education, and trains policy analysts in the fields of foreign policy and national security affairs." (IFPA Homepage, Available:http://www.ifpa.org/). The Institute maintains a core staff of specialists at its offices in Cambridge, Massachusetts and Washington, D.C. IFPA is an affiliate of the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy. Fletcher School faculty and deans have served on the Institution's Board of Directors and Board of Research Consultants. This was an organization supported by the Overseers of the Corporation.

arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by committee meeting date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains material from Tufts University's Administration and Finance Committee from 1856 to 2000. Folders contain meeting announcements, agendas, minutes, letters, budgets, and supplemental materials (i.e., financial reports and articles). Items in this series include the subscriptions (leather bound notebooks) dating to when the trustees were looking for land to build Tufts.

This committee advises the board on management, investment, and reinvestment of all university assets; purchase, exchange, or other disposition of bonds, stocks, and other property; review of independent financial advisors; real estate; gifts; release of assignment of securities; construction and renovation of facilities; and tuition and fee recommendations.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by committee meeting date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains material from Tufts University's Audit Committee from 1976 to 2000. These materials are arranged in chronological order by committee meeting date. Folders contain meeting announcements, agendas, minutes, letters, budgets, and audit reports.

This committee considers and advises the Board and the Executive Committee with respect to the corporation's internal audit procedures, employment of independent certified public accountants, and all matters in connection with independent audits and the formulation of policies or procedures for the avoidance of Trustee conflict of interest. The Audit Committee was created in 1975.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by committee meeting date.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains material from Tufts University's University Advancement Committee from 1975 to 2000. The name of the Committee has varied between "Development" and "Resources" Committee, and is currently called "University Advancement Committee." These materials are arranged in chronological order by committee meeting date. Folders contain announcements, agendas, minutes, memos, and policies.

An ad hoc Committee on Development was created in 1957 as part of a major fundraising effort (The Tufts University Program). It was made a standing committee in 1959. The committee's function is to strengthen the financial resources of the institution.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by committee meeting date.
